  "opinion": "As a woman in my late 40s who works as a plumber in Naples, I've seen firsthand how the gender gap in science isn't just about numbers—it's about the quiet erosion of opportunity. Growing up with a parent who had a master's degree and one who only finished lower secondary school taught me early that education isn't always equally accessible. Now, as someone who spends hours daily on social media, I've noticed how science is often portrayed through a narrow lens, favoring those who seem naturally curious without the support systems many of us need. The gap isn't just in who gets hired—it's in who feels capable of even trying. I've spoken to colleagues who've abandoned STEM fields because they felt like they didn't belong, not because they lacked talent, but because they weren't given the confidence to persist. Addressing this requires more than just data collection; it means creating spaces where women can thrive without having to prove themselves constantly. For me, it starts with simple things—like mentoring young girls in my community through rock climbing clubs, where we discuss science through hands-on activities rather than textbooks. If we want to close the gap, we must stop treating science as a competition and start seeing it as a shared journey. It's not about fixing something broken but building bridges where everyone feels they belong.",
